''Piazza Maggiore — Early December 1629''

Ribbons and banners in red and white lie soggy in the mud of the square. Once bright and proud, they now droop on broken wooden frames, their paint washed away by rain. Market stalls sit overturned, with old fruit rotting on the ground and pottery shards scattered around. Hand-painted posters still read “Padiglione Fair – Procession and Prayers for Bologna,” but below them someone has scrawled “Faith or Folly?” and “Holy Prayer = Death!” in rough black ink.

Wax dripped from spent candles dots the cobblestones, and a single lute with snapped strings lies forgotten in the dirt. A hint of incense still lingers, mixed now with the smell of decay. A chorus of wet coughs echoes from dark doorways, the scrape of mule carts hauling covered bodies toward the Meloncello pits, and overhead the death bell tolls as the Litany of the Saints drifts from St. Petronio’s.

Cardinal-legate Spada steps down from his litter into this smoky, sorrowful scene. Soldiers and purgatori move like ghosts between straw pyres—iron baskets of burning pitch glowing in the dusk—tapping lime-caked canes on doors sealed with wax and red crosses. Families are trapped inside: one man vomits into the gutter; another helper’s tears stain a fresco of the Virgin.  

